India's New Hope
Cambridge, USA — India's latest election could be the most significant positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress party, which had ruled India almost continuously since independence in 1947.
They might feel pleased about this decision.
The leader of the Congress party, former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's widow Sonia Gandhi, has been effectively in charge since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh is merely a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress party pursued populist agendas, increased transfer payments, leading to India's annual GDP growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP remains around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised during the campaign to bring rapid growth in employment and income across all of India, just as he did when he was the Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, with economic activities expanding and attracting commercial investments from both within and outside India.
A key feature of the latest election is that the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), led by Modi, won an absolute majority in the national parliament, which can be considered a remarkable achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will assist Modi in economic planning.
The new finance minister, Arun Jaitley, is politically experienced and served as a minister in the previous BJP government.
Jaitley is also known as a strategic thinker sympathetic to business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the governor of the Reserve Bank of India (central bank). Rajan, an outstanding economist, showed a desire to reduce India's high double-digit annual inflation rate during his tenure and attempted to reform some inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to implement and yield results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine progress in these ten policy areas.
Education.
Despite India's excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of people can access the opportunities they offer, due to the lagging elementary and secondary education in India.
Only 60% of Indian adults have basic literacy skills equivalent to elementary education.
Teachers themselves have low educational attainment and lack motivation, with many teachers not even appearing at their assigned schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products nationwide and around the world.
The expansion of private air routes and airports recently shows that private enterprises can also make a contribution in this area.
Fiscal consolidation.
Large budget deficits absorb national savings that could otherwise be used to expand business investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that must be financed through future taxes.
Privatization.
Indian government-owned manufacturing and other industrial enterprises operate inefficiently, often resulting in the consumption of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly contributes to accelerating economic growth.
Subsidies.
Subsidies for electricity and energy lead to wasteful overconsumption and an increase in fiscal deficits.
Despite these subsidies being politically difficult to eliminate, cash transfers should be implemented instead. Currently, India's cash transfer system is more efficient due to the implementation of a remarkable fingerprint-based cash transfer scheme.
Agricultural reforms.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
As a result, large quantities of goods were stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives were misdirected.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Property rights and regional divisions.
Only regional divisions have constrained optimal land use in towns and cities, such as Mumbai and other major Indian urban centers.
Unclear property rights, especially those related to agricultural land, hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Loosen restrictions on foreign investment.
Currently, foreign enterprises cannot become controlling shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Loosening these restrictions would strengthen the financial sector and play a significant role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
The complex federal and state value-added tax regime in India distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a dual taxation system should now move into the implementation phase.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases undermine economic confidence and hinder official decision-making.
Corruption on a smaller scale also plagues India, with bribery becoming a common feature in all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and curb small-scale corruption through new cash transfer payment systems.
Driven by stronger growth and expectations of rising profits, India's stock market has risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP need to prove to the world that they can deliver on their election promises.
